	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You can certainly do it all without having to buy anything. I have found <a href="http://camstudio.org/" class="postlink">CamStudio</a> to be great for recording the desktop, or any portion of it.
<br />
<br />For the split screen, if you don't mind doing some scripting, <a href="http://avisynth.org/" class="postlink">AviSynth</a> is a great video editor. It doesn't have a GUI, to do your editing you have to type the commands into an .AVS file, and when you open this file in a video player (or encoder, which is how you'll be able to save the result) the software does all the editing you requested in real time. The script to put two videos side by side should be very trivial.
<br />
<br />Also, about the video format, it's not that the codecs used by Flash are popular... You see, downloading an FLV is the same as downloading an MP4, an AVI or an MPG. What people don't want to do is download large files just to watch a few clips. This means that Flash videos are only any good if they can be viewed online just by clicking the "play" button, otherwise it doesn't matter. So just make an account on YouTube an upload your files there, it's the best way to share videos, and what will get you the most viewers.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


