	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Sun Nov 07, 2010 10:19 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">jwdonal wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So just a quick clarification...with this AVIsynth I guess I would initially record my desktop capture and NES video to AVI files, run the appropriate avisynth script on them to get the splitscreen effect, and then upload them to Youtube?</div><br />Yeah, but remember that AviSynth doesn't generate a new AVI file, it just runs your script in real time, so you have to use some video encoder to open the AVS file and encode the results into a new AVI file. A good program for that is <a href="http://www.virtualdub.org/" class="postlink">VirtualDub</a>. Just open the AVS file in it, go to Video-&gt;Compression to pick and configure a codec (you can do the same for the audio if you want to compress it, but you have to switch it to "Full processing mode" instead of "Direct stream copy", because the video is already set like that by default, but not the audio) and finally go to File-&gt;Save as AVI to generate the final file.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I am assuming that youtube will convert my AVI files to flash when I upload them...is that correct?</div>
<br />Yes, YouTube converts it for you. Just make sure you upload a file with decent video quality so that the result doesn't look like shit. Keep in mind that YouTube will be compressing your video for the 3rd time, so don't compress it too much during capture or in VirtualDub, because each time the video is compressed it loses quality.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
