	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>koitsu</b> [ Tue Nov 09, 2010 4:22 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">jwdonal wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><a href="http://koitsu.wordpress.com/2009/09/12/how-to-install-and-use-scfh-dsf/" class="postlink">http://koitsu.wordpress.com/2009/09/12/how-to-install-and-use-scfh-dsf/</a></div><br /><br />Hey Koitsu, that seems pretty easy to install and run (especially after watching the video)...but...how would I do a split-screen effect with it?  Would I still need to use AviSynth for that?<br /><br />Also, what codecs do ya'll like to use when making these videos?  What works best in most cases?  Is it more a matter of personal preference?  I have a pretty blazing fast machine so I should be able to record some high quality video without too much of a problem.<br /><br />Thanks!</div>
<br />
<br />You'd need video editing software to achieve split-screen effects and other whatnots.  Your original post stated that you wanted something that could record your desktop, so I provided such.  :-)
<br />
<br />Regarding codecs: you need to keep in mind that if the videos are for other people there's no guarantee they'll have the codec you used.  Lots of people find the whole "codec installation" thing a PITA (myself included).  Don't forget Macintosh and Linux users too.
<br />
<br />I tend to stick to XviD for video and LAME MP3 ACM for the audio (since XP's built-in MP3 codec doesn't permit higher bit-depth encodings for licensing reasons).  Regarding the audio piece, I use whatever bitrate I want, but the frequency I always have match that of the source (e.g. if recorded at 44kHz 16-bit I use 44kHz 16-bit in LAME MP3 ACM) and I do not use VBR.  Adjusting either of these can cause something you've probably seen before: where the audio gradually gets more and more out of sync with the video.
<br />
<br />XviD codec really isn't intended for things like desktop recording, it's intended for things like film.  There *are* codecs out there specifically intended for "screen capture" stuff -- meaning their compression algos are focused around general desktop composition.  However, as I said before, these codecs aren't always available for all platforms and require people to install them.  YMMV.  I still use XviD even for desktop recording because most people have it already, and if they don't, it's a single no-bullshit installation executable.
<br />
<br />For the actual encoding process, I use VirtualDub, but AviSynth would be totally fine too (assuming you want to deal with writing the scripts yourself).
<br />
<br />Finally, I don't recommend doing both recording and encoding (via codec) at the same time.  Sure, you can do this, but even a hefty multi-core machine will drop frames as a result.  It gets exponentially worse the higher the source resolution; I have a Q9550 (quad-core) CPU, for example, and doing both full desktop (1920x1200) recording + XviD + LAME MP3 encoding all at the same time does drop quite a lot of frames.
<br />
<br />You're better off recording straight to AVI (with both raw audio and video).  Yes the file will be gigantic (multiple gigabytes, depending on the recording length, resolution, etc..), but it gives you the chance to do clean-up and post-processing before encoding.  Otherwise you end up trying to edit a pre-encoded video, then you have to re-encode it again once you make the final cut (which looks like shit; kinda like how people rip DVDs to DivX files; DVD is already MPEG, so they're compressing already-compressed video, which results in Double Blotchy Funtime MPEG Artifact Joy!)

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


