	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Finally, I don't recommend doing both recording and encoding (via codec) at the same time.  Sure, you can do this, but even a hefty multi-core machine will drop frames as a result.  It gets exponentially worse the higher the source resolution; I have a Q9550 (quad-core) CPU, for example, and doing both full desktop (1920x1200) recording + XviD + LAME MP3 encoding all at the same time does drop quite a lot of frames.<br /><br />You're better off recording straight to AVI (with both raw audio and video).  Yes the file will be gigantic (multiple gigabytes, depending on the recording length, resolution, etc..)</div><br />On one of my systems, I have to encode at the same time that I record because my hard disk cannot keep up with the uncompressed stream. Let's do the math: 1920x1200 pixel video at 24 bpp and 30 fps is 1920*1080*24*30 = 1.5 Gbps, which would saturate the bandwidth of the first version of SATA, let alone the bandwidth of the disks connected to it. To record without even a lossless codec such as Huffyuv, one would need 3 Gbps SATA, which means a pretty fat RAID.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">kinda like how people rip DVDs to DivX files; DVD is already MPEG, so they're compressing already-compressed video, which results in Double Blotchy Funtime MPEG Artifact Joy!</div>
<br />But what's the alternative to transcoding if you 1. don't want to move 8 GB files around for a <em>standard</em> definition video and 2. don't have millions of dollars to shoot your own movie?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


