	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Your original post stated that you wanted something that could record your desktop, so I provided such.  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":-)" title="Smile" /></div><br />This will sound like nitpicking, but it would be nice if you explained things a bit instead of just pasting the link (even a simple "Hey, I really like this video capture program, read on my blog about how to set it up" would be better than nothing). Even after I followed your link (something I don't like to do when there is no indication of what the links contain), even the text in the post assumed the reader knew what the tool you were talking about was. I simply gave up trying to find out what it was.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Regarding codecs: you need to keep in mind that if the videos are for other people there's no guarantee they'll have the codec you used.</div><br />Not a problem if you are uploading to YouTube. If you are offering downloads of the original files, your only responsibility is to tell other people where they can download the codec in case they don't have it already.<br /><br />jwdonal, the problem with your videos is thay they are supposed to be half capture of your digital desktop and half capture of analog video of the game running. For the desktop part a lossless codec would work great, but not so much on the analog part (because of the noise it contains). So, for the final encode, you should probably use some standard lossy MPEG-based codec, but with a high bitrate.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">For the actual encoding process, I use VirtualDub, but AviSynth would be totally fine too (assuming you want to deal with writing the scripts yourself).</div><br />AviSynth doesn't encode, it just edits. You still have to run its output through a program that will do the encoding.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Finally, I don't recommend doing both recording and encoding (via codec) at the same time.</div>
<br />Well, maybe not the final, multi-pass, size-oriented, slow encoding, but you have so use <em>some</em> sort of compression when capturing. You simply can't escape having to encode the same video a couple of times, unless you plan to work exclusively with resolutions close to 320x240 a few minutes at a time. Just make sure you use high bitrates for the intermediate encodes and the final result shouldn't suffer too much from artifacts of previous compressions.

		

